In platform/mcp-server/src/plugin-management.ts, lines 83-110, the `runNpmGlobal` function spawns an npm subprocess with a 60s timeout that calls `proc.kill()` (SIGTERM). However, after SIGTERM, the function continues to `await proc.exited` with no secondary guard. If the process ignores SIGTERM, the function hangs forever.

The fix should:
1. After `proc.kill()` (SIGTERM), set a secondary 5s timer that calls `proc.kill('SIGKILL')`
2. Use `Promise.race` to race `proc.exited` against a timeout rejection, so the function never hangs
3. Clean up all timers on both normal and timeout paths

Example approach:
```typescript
const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
  proc.kill();
  // SIGKILL fallback after 5s
  setTimeout(() => { try { proc.kill('SIGKILL'); } catch {} }, 5_000);
}, NPM_SUBPROCESS_TIMEOUT_MS);
```

And for the await, wrap `proc.exited` in a `Promise.race` with a rejection timeout:
```typescript
const exitCode = await Promise.race([
  proc.exited,
  new Promise<never>((_, reject) =>
    setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(`npm ${command} for ${packageName} timed out after ${NPM_SUBPROCESS_TIMEOUT_MS}ms`)), NPM_SUBPROCESS_TIMEOUT_MS + 10_000)
  ),
]);
```

Make sure to clear ALL timeout IDs on the normal exit path. The secondary SIGKILL timer also needs to be cleared if the process exits normally after SIGTERM.

In platform/mcp-server/src/http-routes.ts, line 558, the WebSocket open handler has:
```typescript
void sendSyncFull(state).then(() => {
  if (state.pendingExtensionReload) {
    state.pendingExtensionReload = false;
    log.info('Sending deferred extension reload ...');
    setTimeout(() => sendExtensionReload(state), 500);
  }
});
```

This promise chain has no `.catch()`. If `sendSyncFull` rejects, this becomes an unhandled promise rejection. Compare with platform/mcp-server/src/reload.ts line 152 which correctly uses:
```typescript
void sendSyncFull(state).catch((err: unknown) => {
  log.warn('Failed to send sync.full to extension:', err);
});
```

The fix is to add a `.catch()` at the end of the promise chain in http-routes.ts:
```typescript
void sendSyncFull(state).then(() => {
  if (state.pendingExtensionReload) {
    state.pendingExtensionReload = false;
    log.info('Sending deferred extension reload ...');
    setTimeout(() => sendExtensionReload(state), 500);
  }
}).catch((err: unknown) => {
  log.warn('Failed to send sync.full to extension after WebSocket connect:', err);
});
```

In platform/mcp-server/src/extension-handlers.ts, line 445:
```typescript
const scope = typeof params.scope === 'string' ? (params.scope as ConfirmationScope) : 'tool_domain';
```

This casts any string to `ConfirmationScope` without validation. If the extension sends an invalid scope value (e.g., a typo or protocol version mismatch), the resulting `SessionPermissionRule` will have an invalid `scope` field. When `isSessionAllowed` in platform/mcp-server/src/permissions.ts evaluates this rule, the `switch` statement's `default: return false` means the rule never matches — so the user's 'Allow Always' click silently has no effect.

The fix:
```typescript
const VALID_SCOPES = new Set<string>(['tool_domain', 'tool_all', 'domain_all']);
// ...
const rawScope = typeof params.scope === 'string' ? params.scope : '';
if (rawScope && !VALID_SCOPES.has(rawScope)) {
  log.warn(`Invalid confirmation scope '${rawScope}', falling back to 'tool_domain'`);
}
const scope: ConfirmationScope = VALID_SCOPES.has(rawScope) ? (rawScope as ConfirmationScope) : 'tool_domain';
```

The `VALID_SCOPES` set could be defined as a module-level constant near the top of the file or next to the ConfirmationScope type usage. The `ConfirmationScope` type is defined in platform/mcp-server/src/state.ts line 205 as `'tool_domain' | 'tool_all' | 'domain_all'`.

In platform/mcp-server/src/extension-handlers.ts, line 455:
```typescript
state.sessionPermissions.push(rule);
```

Every 'Allow Always' confirmation unconditionally appends a new rule. Over a long session, this grows without bound. The `isSessionAllowed` function in platform/mcp-server/src/permissions.ts iterates the entire array with `.some()` on every browser tool call.

The fix: before pushing, check if an equivalent rule already exists:
```typescript
const isDuplicate = state.sessionPermissions.some(
  r => r.tool === rule.tool && r.domain === rule.domain && r.scope === rule.scope,
);
if (!isDuplicate) {
  state.sessionPermissions.push(rule);
}
```

Note that `rule.tool` and `rule.domain` can be `null` (for 'tool_all' scope, domain is null; for 'domain_all' scope, tool is null). The `===` comparison handles null correctly (null === null is true).

This is in the `handleConfirmationResponse` function around line 444-456. The `SessionPermissionRule` type is defined in platform/mcp-server/src/state.ts around line 207.

In platform/mcp-server/src/index.ts, lines 146-148:
```typescript
// Load the WebSocket secret from auth.json (single source of truth).
// Also re-read on every reload (reloadCore) so secret rotation takes effect.
state.wsSecret = await loadSecret();
```

This is redundant because `performReload` (called on line 144) already calls `reloadCore` which calls `loadSecret()` and assigns `state.wsSecret` at platform/mcp-server/src/reload.ts line 201:
```typescript
state.wsSecret = await loadSecret();
```

The fix: remove lines 146-148 from index.ts, and remove the `loadSecret` import from line 45:
```typescript
import { loadSecret } from './config.js';
```

Since this is the final story, verify that no other code in index.ts depends on the `loadSecret` import. After removal, `loadSecret` should only be imported in reload.ts and config.ts.

This is the final story — it must have e2eCheckpoint: true to ensure full verification before merge.
